@database "GameX.guide"
@author "Robert Szacki"
@node welcome "Welcome!"

Hello! Welcome to my Amiga Classic game development library. In this
directory you'll find some useful functions used to write games. This is
version 1.0 of library, you can produce very simple games with Bobs
(blitter-objects) with it. So what comes in the current version?

View management functions used to display the graphics on screen (located in
view.c/view.h files).

Shapes loading functions used to load graphics in shape format (this is very
simple format of planar graphics) (located in shapes.c/shapes.h files). The
shape editor will come later, for now you can test simple shape files.

Gameport (joystick) management functions used to receive input from
joystick in simple way. (located in gameport.c/gameport.h files).

Bobs management functions used to display simple animated graphics objects
on screen. (located in bobs.c/bobs.h files).

History:

v1.0  -  initial release
@endnode

@node main "GameX - your game development library"

   GameX - Your game development library (v1.0)

@{" Welcome!               " link welcome} - welcome message from author

@{" View control functions " link view} - description of view component
@{" Shapes functions       " link shapes} - description of shapes component
@{" Gameport functions     " link gameport} - description of gameport component
@{" Bobs functions         " link bobs} - description of bobs component

@endnode
@node view "View control functions"

View management with GameX is simple. First you must call
EstablishViewControl() function which prepares all structures and returns
pointer to ViewControl structure. Then just call SwitchViewControl() once
you're ready to display next animation frame.

When your program exits call ShutdownViewControl().

The value of current off-screen frame is located in ViewControl toggleframe
variable. The pointer to bitmap structure is located in ViewBuffer component
of ViewControl (viewbuf[]).
@endnode
@node shapes "Shapes functions"

Shapes are graphics files that first appeared in game Dune 2. It's simple
format of planar graphics objects with mask. To load shapes just call
LoadShapes() function that loads whole file to memory. Then you can draw the
shape on screen with DrawShape() and DrawMaskedShape() as well as connect
them with Bobs (later described in Bobs section).

The Bitmap structure which you should pass to shape drawing functions is
located in ViewBuffer member of ViewControl structure.
@endnode
@node gameport "Gameport functions"

Gameport is used to receive input from joystick. Just call GetJoystick() to
open the gameport device. Then everytime you need to get joystick state call
GetJoyState(). It returns value 1 if the joystick state changed or 0
otherwise. When you're done call DropJoystick().
@endnode
@node bobs "Bobs functions"

Bobs are animated graphics objects. To create one fill up the NewBob
structure and pass it to CreateMyBob() function.

struct NewBob
{
   WORD  StartX, StartY;      /* Start position of this Bob */
   UWORD *Shapes, ShapeNum;   /* Pointer to Shapes and index */
                              /* of the shape */
   ULONG Flags;               /* Flags (unused in v1.0, set to 0 for now) */
   WORD  AnimSpeed;           /* Speed of animation (unused in v1.0) */
   LONG  (*Animation)(struct MyBob *bob); /* Animation function */
};

Then you're ready to
display Bobs, restore background and store background (it shall be automated
in next release). For this purpose comes RestoreBobBackground(),
StoreBobBackground() and DrawMyBob(). You have to got ready ViewControl
structure to pass to these functions.

To modify Bob just modify its member variables like X (x position on
screen), Y (y position on screen), shape_num (appearance of a Bob).
@endnode

